==Implementation== {{Further|Confederation Period#Struggle for ratification}} In 1787 and 1788, following the Constitutional Convention, a great debate took place throughout the United States over the Constitution that had been proposed. The supporters of the Constitution began the ratification campaign in those states where there was little or no controversy, postponing until later the more difficult ones.
On June 21, 1788, [[New Hampshire]] became the ninth state to ratify the Constitution, thus establishing it as the new framework of governance for the United States. Though officially enacted, four states, [[Virginia]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[North Carolina]] and [[Rhode Island]] remained outside the new government. The Congress of the Confederation chose March 4, 1789 as the day "for commencing proceedings under the Constitution."<ref>{{cite web|title=Article VII. Ratification|url=http://law.justia.com/constitution/us/017-ratification.html|publisher=[[Justia]]}}</ref> Virginia and New York ratified the Constitution before the members of the new [[1st United States Congress|Congress]] assembled on the appointed day to bring the new government into operation.
After twelve amendments, including the ten in the [[United States Bill of Rights|Bill of Rights]], were sent to the states in June 1789, North Carolina ratified the Constitution. Finally, Rhode Island, after having rejected the Constitution in a March 1788 referendum, called a ratifying convention in 1790. Faced with the threat of being treated as a foreign government, it ratified the Constitution by the narrowest margin (two votes).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.archives.gov/education/lessons/constitution-day/ratification.html|title=Observing Constitution Day|date=2016-08-15|work=National Archives|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
